// 1. WHITEPAPER THESIS
// -----------------------------------------------------
//
// DVSM is a deterministic, single-authority state transition kernel
// that produces reproducible system evolution through discrete pulses.
//
// The system explicitly rejects:
//   - nondeterministic execution paths
//   - asynchronous mutation of authoritative state
//   - floating-point dependence in kernel logic
//   - IO-bound or timing-dependent state transitions
//
// All external systems are observational only.
//
// -----------------------------------------------------
// 2. CORE THEORETICAL CLAIM
// -----------------------------------------------------
//
// The DVSM Kernel defines a closed causal loop:
//
//   INPUT → PULSE → STATE TRANSITION → COMMIT → HASH OUTPUT
//
// No external system participates in mutation of authoritative state.
//
// This establishes a bounded, replayable causality domain.
//
// -----------------------------------------------------
// 3. AUTHORITY PRINCIPLE
// -----------------------------------------------------
//
// There exists exactly ONE mutation authority:
//
//   DVSMKernel.commit(state, input)
//
// All other subsystems are strictly observational.
//
// Any system capable of mutation is, by definition,
// part of the Kernel or invalid.
//
// -----------------------------------------------------
// 4. DETERMINISM INVARIANT
// -----------------------------------------------------
//
// Given identical initial state + identical input sequence:
//
//   SYSTEM(t) == SYSTEM'(t)
//
// must hold for all valid execution environments.
//
// Determinism is enforced via:
//   - fixed-point arithmetic in kernel
//   - canonical serialization order
//   - sequence-locked transitions
//   - rejection-preserving lineage continuity
//
// -----------------------------------------------------
// 5. OBSERVATIONAL SEPARATION PRINCIPLE
// -----------------------------------------------------
//
// Systems outside the Kernel are explicitly classified as:
//
//   OBSERVERS (non-authoritative)
//
// Observers may:
//   - read state
//   - compute projections
//   - simulate futures
//   - store historical lineage
//
// Observers may NOT:
//   - mutate kernel state
//   - block kernel execution
//   - influence sequence ordering
//
// -----------------------------------------------------
// 6. FAILURE SEMANTICS
// -----------------------------------------------------
//
// Failure is not collapse.
//
// Failure is a deterministic state transition:
//
//   ACCEPTED  → state evolves
//   REJECTED  → state persists with encoded rejection lineage
//
// Both outcomes advance the system sequence.
//
// No execution path is undefined.
//
// -----------------------------------------------------
// 7. TEMPORAL MODEL
// -----------------------------------------------------
